Surface charge relocation and the geometry configurations of catalysts are decisive factors for the modulating adsorption/desorption behavior of intermediates on the catalyst surface, which can be effectively tuned by rationally designing the interfacial structures of catalysts [2,12]. Hence, the strategy of constructing interfaces has been adapted to improve the catalytic activity in several studies. For instance, Ni(OH)2/Pt (111) heterogeneous catalyst with well-defined interfaces by loading Ni(OH)2 clusters onto Pt (111) surfaces has been proven to be a good alkaline HER electrocatalyst. H2O can be activated and then dissociated on the edges of Ni(OH)2 clusters, while the generated OH* and H* tend to be adsorbed on Ni(OH)2 clusters and nearby Pt surfaces, respectively, achieving the synergistic catalysis between Pt and Ni(OH)2 [9]. In addition, a kind of NiO
                        x
                     @bamboo-like carbon nanotube hybrid (NiO
                        x
                     @BCNTs), with Ni/NiO interfaces, was reported to exhibit improved H* adsorption on the Ni component and water dissociation promoting effect on Ni/NiO interfacial structure, thereby increasing alkaline HER catalytic ability [13]. Although these heterogeneous catalysts with different interfacial structures can improve the HER performance by influencing the adsorption behavior of intermediates, the intermediates adsorption after modulation is still far from the ideal adsorption state, and the long-term stability is not satisfied due to the instability of the interfacial structure, the chemical dissolution of the interfacial components and the breakdown of the heterogeneous structure caused by the large lattice mismatch. Therefore, the rational design of a well-defined interface structure with further optimization of intermediates and higher structural durability is crucial for the practical application of heterogeneous catalysts.
